A 'Thamnophis radix' is a species of snake that belongs to the family Colubridae. 
It is commonly known as the Plains Garter Snake. 
The snake is typically around 2-3 feet in length and has a slender body with a slightly flattened head. 
The color of its skin can vary, but is typically green, brown, or grayish with three yellow stripes running down the length of its body. 
It has small, beady black eyes and a forked tongue which it uses to smell. 
The snake can be found in a variety of habitats, including wetlands, grasslands, and forests, across North America. 
It feeds on small prey such as insects, worms, and small fish.
